@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Cellz" where you want on
your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or Libraries
are needed.

                             How to play?

@{b}Main Menu@{ub}

  In the Main menu, you can choose the total number of cells you and
your opponent want to reach for. That number is displayed in a box at
the right of the slider-like gadget, change that number by clicking
anywhere on the slider-bar. You can also click on the arrows placed
at either end of the slider-bar, this will increase or decrease the
total number by steps of 5 cells.

  When ready to play, just click on the 'Play!' button.

@{b}Game playing@{ub}

  The game itself is played in an area of 20 by 20 spaces which is
surrounded by a wall. On each turn, the players place a cell, by
clicking at a position inside the game area, and a second cell MAY
appear. If a cell do appear, it will always be positioned on a space
next to the cell placed by the player (either at left, right, upward
or downward).

  Each player has his own colour: player 1 plays with the black
cells and player 2 plays with the white ones (note that the colours
may differ if you use a different Workbench palette). When it is
a players turn to play, he (or she) is 'encircled' with his (her)
respective colour.

  The players can place their cells where they want in the game area,
except, of course, where a cell was already placed. If a player put a
cell beside an opponents cell, the opponents cell may change its
colour for the players cell (especially if the space is surrounded
by cells belonging to the opponent!). In fact, an important tactic
of the game is to 'rob' the opponent's cells...

  An arrow on top of the game board indicates, by its direction,
which player has the greatest number of cells. If the arrow is
pointing in both directions, it means that the players have the same
number of cells.

  The game continues until one player has reached the required number
of cells. If the players are tied at that number (or more), the first
one that has one more cell, wins. And as some games, like baseball,
the game is not finished until player 2 has made his (or her) move...

  A game can be aborted at any time by clicking in the close-window
box, this will return to the main menu.

  Have fun!

